  footnotes: []
english:
  title: A Preface to a Poem Presented to Reverend Jogmyeong
  author: Jeong Do-jeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Reverend Musal lay ill at Gajang Temple on Pearl Peak Mountain. One day, Japanese pirates suddenly attacked the temple. In panic, people fled in all directions—some were killed, others taken captive. Yet Reverend Musal's disciple Jogmyeong shouldered his master upon his back and fled, barely escaping with his life.

    I have heard it said that the common people live by three bonds—sovereign, teacher, and father—and serve them all with equal devotion. In circumstances demanding it, they offer up their very lives. So say the scholars of our tradition. But Buddhist monks have abandoned household and world, cast aside their parents as one discards worn cloth. One might think such things hold no place in their hearts.

    Yet mark this: between master and disciple, compassion and righteousness often run so deep, so unrelenting, that when hardship calls, they prove themselves more devoted than any virtuous person or righteous warrior. Such is Jogmyeong's deed. This shows that righteousness dwells inherent in the human heart, impossible to extinguish no matter how one tries. What strange inclination, then, moves those who sever kinship, abandon human bonds, and depart never to return?

    And yet—what stirs naturally in the human heart, once I myself give it voice, awakens in others a response they cannot restrain. Small wonder, then, that so many have taken up the brush to sing this praise.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'The three bonds (three things) mentioned are: sovereign, teacher, and father—foundational relationships in Confucian thought that Jeong Do-jeon, a leading Neo-Confucian thinker, would naturally reference.'
  - key: ''
    value: Jeong Do-jeon contrasts the Confucian emphasis on filial piety and social bonds with Buddhist renunciation, only to find that Buddhist practitioners paradoxically embody these values through their devotion to their masters.
  - key: ''
    value: This preface was written to accompany a poem honoring Jogmyeong's filial devotion to his master during a Japanese pirate raid—an actual historical event during the early Joseon period.
